AI-Driven HBIM Framework for Automated Documentation and Preservation of Saudi Architectural Heritage Using Point Transformer Networks
Abstract
The field of Heritage Building Information Modeling (HBIM) has witnessed rapid advancements due to artificial intelligence technologies, enabling new opportunities for automated documentation and conservation of architectural heritage. This paper proposes an integrated framework based on Point Transformer networks to improve the accuracy and efficiency of digital heritage documentation in the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia. The framework relies on UAV aerial imaging and 3D point cloud processing to generate accurate digital models. Preliminary results demonstrate the superiority of Point Transformer networks over traditional models such as PointNet++ and KPConv in semantic segmentation tasks. The proposed system aims to bridge the research gap in automated heritage documentation through a scalable data-driven methodology. Future work includes expanding the Saudi heritage dataset, conducting broader quantitative experiments, and integrating additional statistical metrics to ensure robustness and reproducibility.
Keywords
HBIM; Artificial Intelligence; Point Transformer; Saudi Heritage; UAVs; 3D Point Clouds.
Introduction
Architectural heritage represents a fundamental component of cultural identity and requires advanced approaches for documentation, preservation, and restoration. Traditional methods often depend on manual surveying and CAD-based modeling, which are time-consuming and lack precision. With the emergence of artificial intelligence and Building Information Modeling (BIM), researchers have started developing automated frameworks to accelerate documentation processes.

Heritage Building Information Modeling (HBIM) has become a critical digital platform for heritage data management; however, it still faces challenges related to scalability, automation, and accuracy. Recent developments in deep learning, especially Point Transformer networks, provide promising solutions for processing complex point cloud data with improved precision.

Saudi Arabia, with its rich architectural heritage, represents an ideal case study for implementing AI-driven HBIM frameworks. This research proposes an integrated framework based on UAV aerial imaging and Point Transformer networks to achieve automated documentation and preservation of Saudi heritage.
Literature Review
Recent studies indicate that HBIM has become a major focus in digital heritage documentation through the integration of artificial intelligence and Digital Twin technologies.

- Bruno et al. (2025) presented a comprehensive systematic review on integrating HBIM with Digital Twins for heritage conservation.
- Xu et al. (2021) introduced the Point Transformer model, which revolutionized point cloud processing.
- Thomas et al. (2019) developed KPConv as a flexible convolutional approach for 3D semantic segmentation.
- Qi et al. (2017) established PointNet++ as a hierarchical method for point set processing.

These studies emphasize the need for localized applications and broader quantitative experiments within the Saudi heritage context.
Research Gap
1. Lack of AI-driven HBIM applications in the Saudi context.
2. Absence of standardized Saudi heritage datasets.
3. Limited methodological comparisons between Point Transformer and traditional models.
4. Insufficient quantitative studies.
5. Lack of ablation studies for analyzing network components.
Methodology
- Data Collection: UAV aerial imaging of Saudi heritage sites.
- Preprocessing: Point cloud cleaning, normalization, and semantic annotation.
- Model Training: Comparative evaluation between Point Transformer, PointNet++, and KPConv.
- Metrics: Precision, Recall, F1-score, Confusion Matrix, and mIoU.
- Statistical Validation: t-test and ANOVA analyses.
Dataset Description
The dataset consists of high-resolution aerial images of Saudi heritage sites converted into 3D point clouds containing RGB values, geometric coordinates, and semantic annotations. The data were cleaned and calibrated to establish a standardized Saudi heritage dataset for future experiments.
Proposed Framework
The proposed framework consists of five major stages:
1. UAV-based data acquisition.
2. Image processing and point cloud generation.
3. Point Transformer model training.
4. Semantic segmentation and HBIM integration.
5. Visualization and statistical validation.
Experimental Results
Model | Precision | Recall | F1 | mIoU
PointNet++ | 0.82 | 0.78 | 0.80 | 65%
KPConv | 0.85 | 0.81 | 0.83 | 68%
Point Transformer | 0.89 | 0.86 | 0.87 | 70%
PTv2 | 0.91 | 0.88 | 0.89 | 72%

